  "chunk_index": 25,
  "summary": "Corston Lindström provides testimony regarding the events surrounding Mrs. Aggles's death. She recalls that after tea, Jacques arrived claiming he had lost his key and went to his mother's room, stating he was in trouble. Corston later witnessed Jacques leaving the house in an angry state, shouting a threat that his mother must have money ready for him \"or else.\" After returning to the house following a flower arrangement contest at approximately 7:30 PM, Corston discovered Mrs. Aggles dead at her desk, with a poker on the floor and desk drawers pulled out. Corston suggests a burglar may have attacked Mrs. Aggles, possibly after being admitted into the house.\n\nMary and Philip Darntes testify that they remained in their separate room playing cards until they heard Corston scream, though Philip notes that Mary's composure seems suspiciously perfect. Other household members provide alibis: Mike claims he was test-driving a car from Dulwich to Ipsley, while Tina, a library worker, states she went home to her flat in the Molkum Building and did not go out.\n\nThe investigation shifts to a suspicious five-pound note found on Jack Aggles, which bears a note on the back. Because Mrs. Aggles had claimed she did not give Jack any money, Inspector Hueston questions Hester about whether she took money from her mother's desk to give to her brother. Hester becomes flustered and contradictory; she initially claims she did not know when Jacques left, but then defensively asserts that she would not steal and that any money given to Jacques would have been her own.",
  "summary_whitespace_tokens": 259,
